(Import [(s5dz ([(Technology (Software (Operations ReleaseEngineering)))] Decision [|Multi-version daemon coexistence via version-suffixed names: persona daemons of different versions run side-by-side on one machine, sockets and CLI binaries named by version (e.g. spirit-v0.1.1), with a shim/alias resolving plain unsuffixed names (spirit) to the environment's current default version. Exact shim mechanism is system-specialist territory.|] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit daemon versioning])) (fosp ([(Technology (Software (Data Persistence)))] Decision [|Sema-engine is the exclusive database boundary: all durable state goes through sema-engine (the SEMA plane that writes to the DB file, currently redb), and no component daemon makes direct redb calls — components are storage-dumb and speak only sema-engine operations. SEMA is a single-writer actor (queries, writes, mutations, additions, upgrades) while reads run parallel over redb MVCC. Component DB files use a .sema extension hiding redb so the name declares its architectural role. For the lojix cutover, build durable DB backing now — daemon live-generation-set, GC-roots, event-log persisted with self-resume on restart — rather than first cutover on in-memory state (durable-first). Internal SEMA work is itself a schema language of messages/commands/responses; a component may keep storage in-daemon first and split it out later using the same language. When schema-derived components expose a reusable storage need, improve the shared engine surface to express their real storage identity rather than porting to a mismatched API. The schema component holds the COMPILED binary runtime schema (packed, short-header O(1) lookup, pre-computed version-diff/namespace tables) while NOTA is the source authoring format. Raw mirror/handover payloads stay in a separate container outside the typed DB.|] VeryHigh Minimum Zero [sema-engine redb sema-file lojix schema-component nota])) (qbx7 ([(Technology (Software (Data Persistence)))] Decision [Spirit timestamp is daemon-stamped] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit timestamp])) (twlp ([(Technology (Software (Data Persistence)))] Principle [Component data lifecycle prefers explicit archival lowering before hard deletion: stale or low-certainty data is marked and moved out of the hot working DB to keep runtime state manageable, recoverability best-effort unless a stronger retention class applies. When a record moves to the archive its privacy variable moves with it, preserved at its original privacy level, and archive reads honor the same explicit privacy discipline as the live store.] Medium Minimum Zero [archive privacy retention])) (k2o1 ([(Technology (Software (Operations DependencyManagement)))] Correction [|Zero consumers does not mean a repo is dead: triad signal-component and meta-signal-component contract repos are MEANT to be used — if a component still emits its contract in-repo rather than depending on its standalone signal-X, the correct action is to adopt and wire it, not delete it (a migration gap, not a tombstone). A repository audit must distinguish intended-but-not-yet-adopted from genuinely-dead by understanding the intended component/triad architecture first.|] VeryHigh Minimum Zero [signal-spirit signal-forge signal-lojix triad repository-audit])) (16l0 ([(Technology (Software (Operations DependencyManagement)))] Decision [When the cloud component is built with the cloudflare feature, flarectl is a runtime dependency: cloud binaries are wrapped via makeWrapper/wrapProgram so flarectl is guaranteed on the daemon PATH at runtime, not relying on the user profile.] High Minimum Zero [cloud cloudflare flarectl nix])) (9huv ([(Technology (Software (Operations DependencyManagement)))] Principle [|Agents using Spirit must track the DEPLOYED version's wire interface, not current persona-spirit source: the deployed pinning is reachable through the CriomOS Home flake input — use Nix metadata commands (flake metadata, derivation show, path-info) to find