y verbs onto signal-cloud (public): Cloudflare is a state the cloud daemon reflects, refresh-by-querying is public, mutations require owner authority — generalising to other providers and any component whose state is a reflected external resource.|] High Medium Zero [cloud cloudflare signal-cloud meta-signal-cloud dns])) (1924 ([(Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Decision [|Editor selection is data, not hardcoded: Horizon user-preference data carries a typed preferred-editor setting per user, and Home/profile configuration consumes that preference instead of hardcoding editor choice downstream (concrete per-user choices live in code/cluster data, not intent-record descriptions). For now, if VSCodium is enabled in a CriomOS-home profile it is the default editor for file-opening links and editor MIME handling, including Markdown and source files such as Rust.|] Medium Minimum Zero [horizon criomos-home vscodium editor-preference])) (242o ([(Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Constraint [Ouranos swap and zram configuration is expressed through cluster data and Horizon projection rather than a host-local CriomOS override.] Medium Minimum Zero [ouranos horizon zram cluster-data])) (cx7y ([(Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Decision [Spirit archive storage should have a sensible daemon-derived default path and be configurable through daemon configuration.] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit archive daemon-config])) (lc28 ([(Technology (Software (Operations ConfigurationManagement)))] Decision [|For the lojix cutover, substituter resolution from node name to Yggdrasil cache URL and public key moves into the daemon (the daemon gains horizon-read for substituters; the wire reverts to carrying bare node names instead of pre-resolved url/public-key pairs). This is a provisional for-now choice and the code must be marked must-be-replaced-by-better-design.|] Low Minimum Zero [lojix substituter yggdrasil horizon])) (6grf ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Decision [|Schema is a specialized NOTA dialect built on structural macro nodes — a schema file is full NOTA, not a separate language lowered into NOTA. Canonical pipeline: authored schema (NOTA) deserializes via the structural-macro-node codec directly into schema-in-rust (typed, rkyv-serializable, canonical round-trip), which then lowers into Rust interface code.|] VeryHigh High Zero [schema nota rkyv schema-in-rust])) (6cfr ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Decision [|The separate Assembled Schema (Asschema) IR is removed: the resolution it performed (inline-declaration hoisting, visibility, ordering, symbol paths) lives as methods on schema-in-rust types used during the lower step, and the emitter does only Rust projection, not schema semantics.|] VeryHigh High Zero [schema asschema schema-in-rust emitter])) (2i75 ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Decision [|Schema imports are selective by name — import specific named types from another schema namespace rather than the whole namespace, using the same names as the source (no rename needed, per-component scope prevents conflicts) and keeping concerns separated per engine/component. Import/name clashes fail within a schema context.|] High Minimum Zero [schema imports namespace])) (vpbx ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation))) (Technology (Software (Programming Macros)))] Decision [|schema-cc is the schema compiler-compiler: the schema language and compiler definition (reference grammar, dispatch precedence, built-in heads, shape vocabulary, emission rules) is kept as typed data that GENERATES the schema compiler (schema-next and schema-rust-next) rather than being hand-written, bottoming out in the nota-next seed. Push as much of the compiler definition into data as possible.|] High Minimum Zero [schema-cc schema-next schema-rust-next nota-next])) (1sa2 ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation